# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: crash-bar
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:crash-bar/access-control] In physical security and information security, **access control** (**AC**) is the action of deciding whether a subject should be granted or denied access to an object (for example, a place or a resource).
[src:crash-bar/access-control] The act of *accessing* may mean consuming, entering, or using.
[src:crash-bar/access-control] It is often used interchangeably with authorization, although the authorization may be granted well in advance of the access control decision.
[src:crash-bar/access-control] Access control on digital platforms is also termed admission control.
[src:crash-bar/access-control] The protection of external databases is essential to preserve digital security.
[src:crash-bar/access-control] Access control is considered to be a significant aspect of privacy that should be further studied.
[src:crash-bar/access-control] **Access control policy** (also **access policy**) is part of an organization’s security policy.
[src:crash-bar/access-control] In order to verify the access control policy, organizations use an access control model.
[src:crash-bar/access-control] General security policies require designing or selecting appropriate security controls to satisfy an organization's risk appetite - access policies similarly require the organization to design or select access controls.
[src:crash-bar/access-control] Broken access control is often listed as the number one risk in web applications.
[src:crash-bar/access-control] On the basis of the "principle of least privilege", consumers should only be authorized to access whatever they need to do their jobs, and nothing more.
[src:crash-bar/access-control] Geographical access control may be enforced by personnel (e.g. border guard, bouncer, ticket checker), or with a device such as a turnstile.
[src:crash-bar/access-control] There may be fences to avoid circumventing this access control.
[src:crash-bar/access-control] An alternative of access control in the strict sense (physically controlling access itself) is a system of checking authorized presence, see e.g.
[src:crash-bar/access-control] A variant is exit control, e.g. of a shop (checkout) or a country.
[src:crash-bar/access-control] The term access control refers to the practice of restricting entrance to a property, a building, or a room to authorized persons.
[src:crash-bar/access-control] Physical access control can be achieved by a human (a guard, bouncer, or receptionist), through mechanical means such as locks and keys, or through technological means such as access control systems like the mantrap.
[src:crash-bar/access-control] Within these environments, physical key management may also be employed as a means of further managing and monitoring access to mechanically keyed areas or access to certain small assets.
[src:crash-bar/access-control] Physical access control is a matter of who, where, and when.
[src:crash-bar/access-control] An access control system determines who is allowed to enter or exit, where they are allowed to exit or enter, and when they are allowed to enter or exit.
[src:crash-bar/access-control] Historically, this was partially accomplished through keys and locks.
[src:crash-bar/access-control] When a door is locked, only someone with a key can enter through the door, depending on how the lock is configured.
[src:crash-bar/access-control] Mechanical locks and keys do not allow restriction of the key holder to specific times or dates.
[src:crash-bar/access-control] Mechanical locks and keys do not provide records of the key used on any specific door, and the keys can be easily copied or transferred to an unauthorized person.
[src:crash-bar/access-control] When a mechanical key is lost or the key holder is no longer authorized to use the protected area, the locks must be re-keyed.
[src:crash-bar/access-control] Electronic access control (EAC) uses computers to solve the limitations of mechanical locks and keys.
[src:crash-bar/access-control] It is particularly difficult to guarantee identification (a critical component of authentication) with mechanical locks and keys.
[src:crash-bar/access-control] A wide range of credentials can be used to replace mechanical keys, allowing for complete authentication, authorization, and accounting.
[src:crash-bar/access-control] The electronic access control system grants access based on the credential presented.
[src:crash-bar/access-control] When access is granted, the resource is unlocked for a predetermined time and the transaction is recorded.
[src:crash-bar/access-control] When access is refused, the resource remains locked and the attempted access is recorded.
[src:crash-bar/access-control] The system will also monitor the resource and alarm if the resource is forcefully unlocked or held open too long after being unlocked.
[src:crash-bar/access-control] When a credential is presented to a reader, the reader sends the credential's information, usually a number, to a control panel, a highly reliable processor.
[src:crash-bar/access-control] The control panel compares the credential's number to an access control list, grants or denies the presented request, and sends a transaction log to a database.
[src:crash-bar/access-control] When access is denied based on the access control list, the door remains locked.
[src:crash-bar/access-control] If there is a match between the credential and the access control list, the control panel operates a relay that in turn unlocks the resource.
[src:crash-bar/access-control] The control panel also ignores an opening signal to prevent an alarm.
[src:crash-bar/access-control] Often the reader provides feedback, such as a flashing red LED for an access denied and a flashing green LED for an access granted.
[src:crash-bar/access-control] The above description illustrates a single factor transaction.
[src:crash-bar/access-control] Credentials can be passed around, thus subverting the access control list.
[src:crash-bar/access-control] For example, Alice has access rights to the server room, but Bob does not.
[src:crash-bar/access-control] Alice either gives Bob her credential, or Bob takes it; he now has access to the server room.
[src:crash-bar/access-control] To prevent this, two-factor authentication can be used.
[src:crash-bar/access-control] In a two factor transaction, the presented credential and a second factor are needed for access to be granted; another factor can be a PIN code, a second credential, operator intervention, or a biometric input.
[src:crash-bar/access-control] Passwords are a common means of verifying a user's identity before access is given to information systems.
[src:crash-bar/access-control] In addition, a fourth factor of authentication is now recognized: someone you know, whereby another person who knows you can provide a human element of authentication in situations where systems have been set up to allow for such scenarios.
[src:crash-bar/access-control] For example, a user may have their password, but have forgotten their smart card.
[src:crash-bar/access-control] In such a scenario, if the user is known to designated cohorts, the cohorts may provide their smart card and password, in combination with the extant factor of the user in question, and thus provide two factors for the user with the missing credential, giving three factors overall to allow access.
[src:crash-bar/access-control] A credential is a physical/tangible object, a piece of knowledge, or a facet of a person's physical being that enables an individual access to a given physical facility or computer-based information system.
[src:crash-bar/access-control] Typically, credentials can be something a person knows (such as a number or PIN code), something they have (such as an access badge), something they are (such as a biometric feature), something they do (measurable behavioural patterns), or some combination of these items.
[src:crash-bar/access-control] This is known as multi-factor authentication.
[src:crash-bar/access-control] The typical credential is an access card or key-fob, and newer software can also turn users' smartphones into access devices.
[src:crash-bar/access-control] There are many card technologies including magnetic stripe, bar code, Wiegand, 125 kHz proximity, 26-bit card-swipe, contact smart cards, and contactless smart cards.
[src:crash-bar/access-control] Also available are key-fobs, which are more compact than ID cards, and attach to a key ring.
[src:crash-bar/access-control] Biometric technologies include fingerprint, facial recognition, iris recognition, retinal scan, voice, and hand geometry.
[src:crash-bar/access-control] The built-in biometric technologies found on newer smartphones can also be used as credentials in conjunction with access software running on mobile devices.
[src:crash-bar/access-control] In addition to older more traditional card access technologies, newer technologies such as near-field communication (NFC), Bluetooth low energy or Ultra-wideband (UWB) can also communicate user credentials to readers for system or building access.
[src:crash-bar/access-control] Access control decisions are made by comparing the credentials to an access control list.
[src:crash-bar/access-control] This look-up can be done by a host or server, by an access control panel, or by a reader.
[src:crash-bar/access-control] The development of access control systems has observed a steady push of the look-up out from a central host to the edge of the system, or the reader.
[src:crash-bar/access-control] The predominant topology circa 2009 is hub and spoke with a control panel as the hub, and the readers as the spokes.
[src:crash-bar/access-control] The look-up and control functions are by the control panel.
[src:crash-bar/access-control] The spokes communicate through a serial connection; usually RS-485.
[src:crash-bar/access-control] Some manufactures are pushing the decision making to the edge by placing a controller at the door.
[src:crash-bar/access-control] Some readers may have additional features such as a display and function buttons for data collection purposes (i.e. clock-in/clock-out events for attendance reports), camera/speaker/microphone for intercom, or smart card read/write support.
[src:crash-bar/access-control] All the RS-485-related advantages and disadvantages also apply.
[src:crash-bar/access-control] The advantages and disadvantages of IP controllers apply to the IP readers as well.
[src:crash-bar/access-control] The most common security risk of intrusion through an access control system is by simply following a legitimate user through a door, referred to as "tailgating".
[src:crash-bar/access-control] Often, a legitimate user may hold the door for the intruder as an act of common courtesy.
[src:crash-bar/access-control] This risk can be minimized through security awareness training of the user population, or more active means such as turnstiles which admit only one person at a time.
[src:crash-bar/access-control] In very high-security applications, this risk is minimized by using a sally port (sometimes called a "security vestibule" or "mantrap"), where operator intervention is required, presumably after confirming valid identification.
[src:crash-bar/access-control] The second most common risk is from levering a door open by sheer brute force.
[src:crash-bar/access-control] This is relatively difficult on properly-secured doors with ruggedized strikes or high holding force magnetic locks.
[src:crash-bar/access-control] Fully-implemented access control systems include forced-door monitoring alarms.
[src:crash-bar/access-control] These vary in effectiveness, often failing from high false-positive alarms, poor database configuration, or lack of active intrusion monitoring.
[src:crash-bar/access-control] Most newer access control systems incorporate some type of "door prop" alarm to inform system administrators of a door left open longer than a specified length of time.
[src:crash-bar/access-control] The third most common security risk arises from natural disasters.
[src:crash-bar/access-control] In order to mitigate this risk, the structure of the building, down to the quality of the network and computer equipment is crucial.
[src:crash-bar/access-control] From an organizational perspective, the leadership will need to adopt and implement an All Hazards Plan, or Incident Response Plan.
[src:crash-bar/access-control] The highlights of any incident plan recommended by the National Incident Management System usually include pre-incident planning, during-incident actions, disaster recovery, and after-action review.
[src:crash-bar/access-control] An attack similar to levering is breaking through cheap partition walls, typically made of wallboard or cinder blocks.
[src:crash-bar/access-control] In shared tenant spaces, the divisional wall is a vulnerability.
[src:crash-bar/access-control] A vulnerability along the same lines is the breaking of sidelight windows located next to doors.
[src:crash-bar/access-control] Spoofing of locking hardware is fairly simple and more elegant than levering.
[src:crash-bar/access-control] A strong magnet can operate the solenoid controlling bolts in electric locking hardware.
[src:crash-bar/access-control] Motorized locks, more prevalent in Europe than in the US, are also susceptible to this attack using a doughnut-shaped magnet.
[src:crash-bar/access-control] It is also possible to manipulate the power to the lock either by removing or adding current, although most Access Control systems incorporate battery back-up systems, and the locks are almost always located on the secure side of the door.
[src:crash-bar/access-control] Access cards themselves have proven vulnerable to sophisticated attacks.
[src:crash-bar/access-control] Enterprising hackers have built portable readers that capture the card number from a user's proximity card.
[src:crash-bar/access-control] The hacker simply walks by the user, reads the card, and later presents the number to a reader securing the door.
[src:crash-bar/access-control] This is possible when card numbers are sent in the clear, no encryption being used.
[src:crash-bar/access-control] To counter this, dual authentication methods, such as a card plus a PIN should always be used.
[src:crash-bar/access-control] Many access control credentials use unique serial numbers which are programmed in sequential order during manufacturing.
[src:crash-bar/access-control] In a method known as a "sequential attack", if an intruder has a credential once used in the system, they can simply increment or decrement the serial number until they find a credential that is currently authorized in the system.
[src:crash-bar/access-control] Specifying credentials with random unique serial numbers is recommended to counter this threat.
[src:crash-bar/access-control] In addition, increasingly long lockout timeout intervals after a credential failure will make automated repeated attacks infeasible.
[src:crash-bar/access-control] Finally, most electric locking hardware still uses mechanical keys as a fail-over.
[src:crash-bar/access-control] Most conventional mechanical key locks are vulnerable to bumping.
[src:crash-bar/access-control] In computer security, general access control includes authentication, authorization, and audit.
[src:crash-bar/access-control] A more narrow definition of access control would cover only access approval, whereby the system makes a decision to grant or reject an access request from an already authenticated subject, based on what the subject is authorized to access.
[src:crash-bar/access-control] Authentication and access control are often combined into a single operation, so that access is approved based on successful authentication, or based on an anonymous access token.
[src:crash-bar/access-control] Authentication methods and tokens include passwords, biometric analysis, physical keys, electronic keys and devices, hidden paths, social barriers, and monitoring by humans and automated systems.
[src:crash-bar/access-control] In any access-control model, the entities that can perform actions on the system are called *subjects*, and the entities representing resources to which access may need to be controlled are called *objects* (see also Access Control Matrix).
[src:crash-bar/access-control] Subjects and objects should both be considered as software entities, rather than as human users: any human users can only have an effect on the system via the software entities that they control.
[src:crash-bar/access-control] In some models, for example the object-capability model, any software entity can potentially act as both subject and object.
[src:crash-bar/access-control] As of 2014, access-control models tend to fall into one of two classes: those based on capabilities and those based on access control lists (ACLs).
[src:crash-bar/access-control] Both capability-based and ACL-based models have mechanisms to allow access rights to be granted to all members of a *group* of subjects (often the group is itself modeled as a subject).
[src:crash-bar/access-control] Access to accounts can be enforced through many types of controls.
[src:crash-bar/access-control] Discretionary Access Control (DAC) In DAC, the data owner determines who can access specific resources.
[src:crash-bar/access-control] For example, a system administrator may create a hierarchy of files to be accessed based on certain permissions.
[src:crash-bar/access-control] Graph-based Access Control (GBAC) Compared to other approaches like RBAC or ABAC, the main difference is that in GBAC access rights are defined using an organizational query language instead of total enumeration.
[src:crash-bar/access-control] History-Based Access Control (HBAC) Access is granted or declined based on the real-time evaluation of a history of activities of the inquiring party, e.g. behavior, time between requests, content of requests.
[src:crash-bar/access-control] For example, the access to a certain service or data source can be granted or declined on the personal behavior, e.g. the request interval exceeds one query per second.
[src:crash-bar/access-control] History-of-Presence Based Access Control (HPBAC) Access control to resources is defined in terms of presence policies that need to be satisfied by presence records stored by the requestor.
[src:crash-bar/access-control] Policies are usually written in terms of frequency, spread and regularity.
[src:crash-bar/access-control] Identity-Based Access Control (IBAC) Using this network administrators can more effectively manage activity and access based on individual needs.
[src:crash-bar/access-control] Lattice-Based Access Control (LBAC) A lattice is used to define the levels of security that an object may have and that a subject may have access to.
[src:crash-bar/access-control] The subject is only allowed to access an object if the security level of the subject is greater than or equal to that of the object.
[src:crash-bar/access-control] Mandatory Access Control (MAC) In MAC, users do not have much freedom to determine who has access to their files.
[src:crash-bar/access-control] For example, security clearance of users and classification of data (as confidential, secret or top secret) are used as security labels to define the level of trust.
[src:crash-bar/access-control] Organization-Based Access Control (OrBAC) OrBAC model allows the policy designer to define a security policy independently of the implementation.
[src:crash-bar/access-control] Relationship-Based Access Control (ReBAC) A subject's permission to access a resource is defined by the presence of relationships between those subjects and resources.
[src:crash-bar/access-control] Role-Based Access Control (RBAC) RBAC allows access based on the job title.
[src:crash-bar/access-control] RBAC largely eliminates discretion when providing access to objects.
[src:crash-bar/access-control] For example, a human resources specialist should not have permissions to create network accounts; this should be a role reserved for network administrators.
[src:crash-bar/access-control] Rule-Based Access Control (RAC) RAC method, also referred to as Rule-Based Role-Based Access Control (RB-RBAC), is largely context based.
[src:crash-bar/access-control] Example of this would be allowing students to use labs only during a certain time of day; it is the combination of students' RBAC-based information system access control with the time-based lab access rules.
[src:crash-bar/access-control] Responsibility Based Access Control Information is accessed based on the responsibilities assigned to an actor or a business role.
[src:crash-bar/access-control] Subscription-Based Access Control (SBAC) SBAC assigns permissions based on a user's subscription status, automating the process of granting, modifying, or revoking access as users subscribe, upgrade, downgrade, or cancel.
[src:crash-bar/access-control] SBAC is particularly relevant for SaaS business, where access to features, data, or services is tied to a user's active plan.
[src:crash-bar/access-control] Unlike RBAC or ABAC, which define permissions based on roles or attributes, SBAC dynamically distributes roles and policies based on billing status, ensuring real-time access alignment.
[src:crash-bar/access-control] Several regulatory frameworks impose specific access control requirements on organizations handling sensitive data.
[src:crash-bar/access-control] The HIPAA Security Rule requires covered entities and business associates to implement technical access controls for electronic protected health information (ePHI), including unique user identification, emergency access procedures, automatic logoff, and encryption and decryption mechanisms.
[src:crash-bar/access-control] The proposed HIPAA Security Rule update (NPRM, December 2024) would strengthen these requirements by mandating multi-factor authentication for all access to ePHI.
[src:crash-bar/access-control] The Payment Card Industry Data Security Standard (PCI DSS) Requirement 7 mandates that access to cardholder data be restricted on a need-to-know basis, while Requirement 8 requires unique identification for each person with computer access.
[src:crash-bar/access-control] The National Institute of Standards and Technology (NIST) addresses access control extensively in Special Publication 800-53 through the AC (Access Control) control family, which includes policies for account management, separation of duties, least privilege, and session controls.
[src:crash-bar/access-control] A technique used to define or restrict the rights of individuals or application programs to obtain data from, or place data onto, a storage device.
[src:crash-bar/access-control] The definition or restriction of the rights of individuals or application programs to obtain data from, or place data into, a storage device.
[src:crash-bar/access-control] The process of limiting access to the resources of an AIS (Automated Information System) to authorized users, programs, processes, or other systems.
[src:crash-bar/access-control] That function performed by the resource controller that allocates system resources to satisfy user requests.
[src:crash-bar/access-control] This definition depends on several other technical terms from Federal Standard 1037C.
[src:crash-bar/access-control] Special public member methods – **accessors** (aka **getters**) and **mutator methods** (often called **setters**) are used to control changes to class variables in order to prevent unauthorized access and data corruption.
[src:crash-bar/access-control] In public policy, access control to restrict access to systems ("authorization") or to track or monitor behavior within systems ("accountability") is an implementation feature of using trusted systems for security or social control.
[src:crash-bar/active-fire-protection] Manual fire suppression includes the use of a fire blanket, fire extinguisher, or a standpipe system.
[src:crash-bar/active-fire-protection] A fire blanket is a sheet of fire retardant material that is designed to be placed over a fire to smother it out.
[src:crash-bar/active-fire-protection] Small fire blankets are meant for inception stage fires.
[src:crash-bar/active-fire-protection] They are normally made of fiberglass or Kevlar.
[src:crash-bar/active-fire-protection] Larger ones can be found in laboratories and factories, and are designed to be wrapped around a person whose clothes have caught fire.
[src:crash-bar/active-fire-protection] Fire extinguishers are devices that contain and discharge a substance that extinguishes or puts out a fire.
[src:crash-bar/active-fire-protection] These handheld devices come in a huge range of sizes, but the most common are portable fire extinguishers, typically weighing up to 15 kg in total.
[src:crash-bar/active-fire-protection] These can be easily handled and operated by one person and placement can either be wall-mounted, on a fire extinguisher trolley or housed inside a cabinet.
[src:crash-bar/active-fire-protection] Fire extinguishers are one of the most common manual fire suppression devices and are required in all commercial buildings and vehicles.
[src:crash-bar/active-fire-protection] Fire extinguishers can be used with little to no training and are meant for small incipient stage fires.
[src:crash-bar/active-fire-protection] The most common extinguisher is the ABC extinguisher and are found in most offices and homes.
[src:crash-bar/active-fire-protection] It can be used on normal fires, liquid fires, and electrical fires.
[src:crash-bar/active-fire-protection] There are also special extinguishers for kitchen fires and for use on burning metals, those being Class K and Class D respectively.
[src:crash-bar/active-fire-protection] Standpipes are installed in most large, multistory buildings.
[src:crash-bar/active-fire-protection] There are two types of standpipes: dry and wet.
[src:crash-bar/active-fire-protection] Most standpipes are dry systems and cannot be used by the public.
[src:crash-bar/active-fire-protection] Dry systems require a fire engine to pump water into the system.
[src:crash-bar/active-fire-protection] Most dry systems do not have pre-connected hoses and require firefighters to bring in the hose.
[src:crash-bar/active-fire-protection] In wet systems, there is always water in the pipes and they can be used by anyone.
[src:crash-bar/active-fire-protection] Wet systems will have hoses so building occupants can try and extinguish fires.
[src:crash-bar/active-fire-protection] Wet systems are becoming less common with the increase in number of sprinkler systems being installed.
[src:crash-bar/active-fire-protection] In some systems, firefighters have the option of pumping a Fire Department Connection (FDC) which will increase the water pressure at a standpipe in the event of a fire pump failure or loss of pressure.
[src:crash-bar/active-fire-protection] Typically, these systems pressurize the sprinkler system or the standpipe but not both at the same time.
[src:crash-bar/active-fire-protection] Automatic control means are any form of suppression that requires no human intervention these can include a fire sprinkler system, a gaseous clean agent, or automatic foam suppression system.
[src:crash-bar/active-fire-protection] Most automatic suppression systems would be found in large commercial kitchens or other high-risk areas.
[src:crash-bar/active-fire-protection] Fire sprinkler systems are installed in all types of buildings, commercial and residential.
[src:crash-bar/active-fire-protection] They are usually located at ceiling level and are connected to a reliable water source, most commonly municipal water supply.
[src:crash-bar/active-fire-protection] A typical automatic sprinkler system operates when heat at the site of a fire causes a fusible link or glass component in the sprinkler head to fail, thereby releasing the water from the sprinkler head.
[src:crash-bar/active-fire-protection] This means that only the sprinkler heads at the fire location actuate – not all the sprinklers on a floor or in a building.
[src:crash-bar/active-fire-protection] However, certain systems, such as deluge systems, do spray water from all heads in the same zone upon actuation.
[src:crash-bar/active-fire-protection] Sprinkler systems help to reduce the growth of a fire, thereby increasing life safety and limiting structural damage.
[src:crash-bar/active-fire-protection] Gaseous clean agents are installed to result in less fire and water damage than sprinklers, such as in computer rooms.
[src:crash-bar/active-fire-protection] The system works by flooding an area with a gas which interferes with the fire tetrahedron.
[src:crash-bar/active-fire-protection] These systems are often found in areas where people are not going to be present when the system is activated such as datacenters, cooling systems, and other industrial applications.
[src:crash-bar/active-fire-protection] Activating a gaseous clean agent system when people are present can cause injury or death, and are usually equipped with an audible notification system to warn any potential occupants to evacuate the area.
[src:crash-bar/active-fire-protection] Automatic foam suppression systems come in three main forms low expansion, medium expansion, and high expansion.
[src:crash-bar/active-fire-protection] Low expansion foam expands less than 20 times its original size.
[src:crash-bar/active-fire-protection] These systems can be installed in a variety of places but are commonly found in places where hydrocarbons are stored.
[src:crash-bar/active-fire-protection] Low expansion foam systems when using film forming work by making a blanket of foam over the burning liquid to both cool it down and suppress the vapors.
[src:crash-bar/active-fire-protection] Medium expansion foam expands between 20 and 200 times its original size.
[src:crash-bar/active-fire-protection] These can be installed in outdoor settings like transfer stations or for use in open pits.
[src:crash-bar/active-fire-protection] Medium foam is used outdoors because it is denser than high expansion and will not blow away as easily.
[src:crash-bar/active-fire-protection] It works by covering what is on fire in a thick blanket of foam to smother it and suppress vapors.
[src:crash-bar/active-fire-protection] High expansion foam expands between 200 and 1000 times its original size.
[src:crash-bar/active-fire-protection] These systems are commonly installed in large volume areas like airplane hangars, mine shafts, and ship holds.
[src:crash-bar/active-fire-protection] These systems are normally installed inside and make a very light foam.
[src:crash-bar/active-fire-protection] They extinguish the fire by rapid smothering and cooling.
[src:crash-bar/active-fire-protection] Its rapid rate of expansion enables it to fill large areas with foam rapidly.
[src:crash-bar/active-fire-protection] When used on LNG tanks they provide an added insulation layer that helps reduce the vapor rate.
[src:crash-bar/active-fire-protection] Nozzles that are powered by electrical energy that is generated and supplied by fire detection and control devices and are typically closed.
[src:crash-bar/active-fire-protection] ILDFA uses a dual approach, combining a water-based fire suppression system in conjunction with a hollow, perforated flooring system to drain and remove spilled flammable liquid.
[src:crash-bar/active-fire-protection] This approach reduces the risk of pool fires inside infrastructure by diverting any leaked fuel away from potential ignition sources or by extinguishing any flammable liquid fire by depriving it of oxygen once it is removed.
[src:crash-bar/active-fire-protection] Fire detection works using smoke or heat sensors.
[src:crash-bar/active-fire-protection] These systems are very effective tool at alerting people in the immediate vicinity of where the fire is detected but building regulations require an integrated fire detection system.
[src:crash-bar/active-fire-protection] These system not only alerts people throughout the building by triggering the fire alarm but it can also summon emergency services.
[src:crash-bar/active-fire-protection] There are two types of systems available – addressable and conventional.
[src:crash-bar/active-fire-protection] Addressable systems monitor the specific location of each device (e.g. smoke detector, call point or sounder).
[src:crash-bar/active-fire-protection] It means in the event of a fire or other emergency you know exactly where the problem is.
[src:crash-bar/active-fire-protection] This saves precious time and helps the emergency services prevent the loss of life and serious damage.
[src:crash-bar/active-fire-protection] Conventional systems can only determine the problem is in a general area and thus are more suited for small sites.
[src:crash-bar/active-fire-protection] When the fire detection system is activated it can also send an alert to the local fire department, broadcast a prerecorded warning message and unlock the buildings access control system.
[src:crash-bar/active-fire-protection] Hypoxic air fire prevention systems, also known as oxygen reduction systems are new automatic fire prevention systems that permanently reduce the oxygen concentration inside the protected volumes so that ignition or fire spreading cannot occur.
[src:crash-bar/active-fire-protection] Unlike traditional fire suppression systems that usually extinguish fire after it is detected, hypoxic air is able to prevent fires.
[src:crash-bar/active-fire-protection] At lower altitudes hypoxic air is safe to breathe for healthy individuals.
[src:crash-bar/active-fire-protection] All AFP systems are required to be installed and maintained in accordance with strict guidelines in order to maintain compliance with the local building code and the fire code.
[src:crash-bar/active-fire-protection] AFP works alongside modern architectural designs and construction materials and fire safety education to prevent, retard, and suppress structural fires.
[src:crash-bar/alarm-device] An **alarm device** is a mechanism that gives an audible, visual, combination, or other kind of alarm signal to alert someone to a problem or condition that requires urgent attention.
[src:crash-bar/alarm-device] The word *alarm* comes from the Old French *a l'arme* meaning "to the arms", or "to the weapons", telling armed men to pick up their weapons and get ready for action because an enemy may have suddenly appeared.
[src:crash-bar/alarm-device] The word *alarum* is an archaic form of *alarm*.
[src:crash-bar/alarm-device] It was sometimes used as a call to arms in the stage directions of Elizabethan dramas.
[src:crash-bar/alarm-device] The term comes from the Italian *all'armi* and appears 89 times in Shakespeare's First Folio.
[src:crash-bar/alarm-device] Often explained as the off-stage sounds of conflict or disturbance, recent research suggests a bell or drum may have been used to rouse soldiers from sleep.
[src:crash-bar/alarm-device] Early alarm devices were often bells, drums, other musical instruments, or any items which made unusual loud noises that attracted the attention of the surrounding population.
[src:crash-bar/alarm-device] Whistles were used by police in the 19th century.
[src:crash-bar/alarm-device] Steam whistles have been used on locomotives, ships, and in factories as alarm devices.
[src:crash-bar/alarm-device] With the advent of electricity, a variety of other alerting devices have been invented, such as buzzers, klaxons, sirens, horns, flashing and coloured lights, and other all-purpose alarms.
[src:crash-bar/alarm-device] Alarm devices can be fitted to buildings as well as vehicles.
[src:crash-bar/alarm-device] Many buildings are fitted with fire alarms, ranging from a self-contained domestic smoke detector to a sophisticated alarm system that can operate building fire fighting systems automatically to extinguish fires with water or inert gases.
[src:crash-bar/alarm-device] Many industries have developed standards for alarm devices, and the colours red, blue and amber are generally recognized as alarm device-related colours, with flashing lights often indicating urgent conditions.
[src:crash-bar/alarm-device] Human reactions to an alarm will often depend on upbringing, psychological training, or the behavior of others in the environment.
[src:crash-bar/alarm-device] Consequently, the ability to test an alarm and hold regular drills to practice an appropriate response may be provided as part of an alarm system.
[src:crash-bar/alarm-device] Alarm devices that are intended to cause the evacuation of an occupied building, such as fire alarms, may be deliberately designed to make remaining in the space difficult or even painful in order to encourage occupants to leave.
[src:crash-bar/alarm-device] Some alarms may startle and cause a fight-or-flight response in humans; a person under this mindset will panic and either flee the perceived danger or attempt to eliminate it, often ignoring rational thought in either case.
[src:crash-bar/alarm-device] A person in such a state can be characterized as "alarmed".
[src:crash-bar/alarm-device] With any kind of alarm, people must balance between the danger of false alarms (called "false positives") — the signal going off in the absence of a problem — or an alarm failing to signal an actual problem (called a "false negative").
[src:crash-bar/alarm-device] False alarms can waste resources expensively and can even be dangerous.
[src:crash-bar/alarm-device] For example, false alarms of a fire can waste firefighter manpower, making them unavailable for a real fire, and risk injury to firefighters and others as the fire engines race to the alleged fire's location.
[src:crash-bar/alarm-device] In addition, false alarms may acclimatise people to ignore alarm signals, and thus possibly to ignore an actual emergency: Aesop's fable of *The Boy Who Cried Wolf* exemplifies this problem.
[src:crash-bar/alarm-device] A false alarm is one of the most significant issues with conventional alarm systems.
[src:crash-bar/alarm-device] They can be triggered for several reasons, such as the movement of pets, typing in the wrong security codes, or loud sounds from windows or doors.
[src:crash-bar/alarm-device] In the case of fire alarms, aerosol sprays, smoking, or burning food can all lead to a false alarm.
[src:crash-bar/alarm-device] Many avoid the risk of false alarms by ensuring their alarms are secured in an appropriate location, such as placing a smoke detector or fire alarm away from the kitchen where smoke from burned food or large quantities of steam which may trigger a false alarm are common occurrences.
[src:crash-bar/alarm-device] In the case of a security alarm, an additional monitoring station which assesses whether there is a legitimate need for help can reduce false alarms.
[src:crash-bar/alarm-monitoring-center] An **alarm monitoring center**, **central monitoring station** (also known as "CMS" or wholesale central station), or **alarm receiving center** (also known as **ARC**) is a company that provides services to monitor burglar, fire, and residential alarm systems.
[src:crash-bar/alarm-monitoring-center] The Central Monitoring Station may also provide watchman and supervisory services.
[src:crash-bar/alarm-monitoring-center] Central monitoring stations use special telephone and mobile lines, radio channels, computers, software and trained staff to monitor their customers' security systems and call the appropriate authorities in the event an alarm signal is received.
[src:crash-bar/alarm-monitoring-center] Typically, there is a monthly fee for services rendered.
[src:crash-bar/alarm-monitoring-center] Because quality and experience can vary greatly among alarm companies, prospective customers are well advised to do their own research before making a final choice.
[src:crash-bar/alarm-monitoring-center] Not all alarm companies monitor the systems they install and may outsource these services to another company.
[src:crash-bar/alarm-monitoring-center] Some facilities are certified by independent agencies.
[src:crash-bar/alarm-monitoring-center] In the US, Underwriters Laboratories (UL) is a leader in inspection and certification of central-stations.
[src:crash-bar/alarm-monitoring-center] UL Standard 827 must be adhered to in order to maintain a UL issued central-station listing.
[src:crash-bar/alarm-monitoring-center] UL conducts annual audits of these listed facilities to ensure compliance.
[src:crash-bar/alarm-monitoring-center] "UL listed" companies typically offer higher levels of service and reliability because they are mandated to follow certain regulations.
[src:crash-bar/alarm-monitoring-center] Higher levels of service also include range of services, and a separation from companies with conflicts of interest who may be owned or operated by entities that in fact compete with the central station's customers.
[src:crash-bar/alarm-monitoring-center] If the UL listed central station is "automated", the computers and software must meet special requirements, processing and storing very large amounts of data and integration with many different alarm protocols.
[src:crash-bar/alarm-monitoring-center] In addition, many central monitoring stations seek to become FM approved in order to demonstrate additional levels of regulation compliance and interest for customer safety.
[src:crash-bar/alarm-monitoring-center] Incoming signals are processed by digital alarm receivers; these convert the incoming event packets to serial or TCP packets which are then analysed by the Central Station software.
[src:crash-bar/alarm-monitoring-center] Event packets can be communicated over any transmission medium: PSTN, GSM, radio, direct line, Ethernet, GPRS, etc.
[src:crash-bar/alarm-monitoring-center] In the United States, central stations are regulated by third-party inspection companies such as Underwriters Laboratories (UL), FM Approvals, and The Monitoring Association (TMA).
[src:crash-bar/alarm-monitoring-center] Central stations are evaluated on specific criteria such as system redundancy, building security, and regulation compliance.
[src:crash-bar/alarm-monitoring-center] Once a central station has demonstrated adherence to the UL requirements, it can receive its certification.
[src:crash-bar/alarm-monitoring-center] Incorporated in 1950, TMA is legally entitled to represent its members before Congress and regulatory agencies on the local, state and federal levels, and other authorities having jurisdiction (AHJs) over the industry.
[src:crash-bar/alarm-monitoring-center] The Monitoring Association also inspects and certifies central stations.
[src:crash-bar/alarm-monitoring-center] In Australia, central stations are graded against Australian Standard 2201.2 which addresses both physical construction and operational performance.
[src:crash-bar/alarm-monitoring-center] Physical performance is graded A, B or C (where A is the highest grading) and includes measures such as the construction of monitoring rooms – higher security monitoring centres have solid concrete and steel construction with mantraps for access that can only be operated internally.
[src:crash-bar/alarm-monitoring-center] Operational performance is graded 1, 2 or 3 (with one being the highest grading).
[src:crash-bar/alarm-monitoring-center] It includes the ability of the monitoring centre to respond to events – generated by customers' security systems, operational reliability, data retrieval, etc.
[src:crash-bar/alarm-monitoring-center] Accordingly, the highest grading is A1 and the lowest is C3 however even to be graded at C3 central stations still meet very high standards.
[src:crash-bar/alarm-monitoring-center] There is presently no legislative imperative for an Australian central station to be 'graded' however police may refuse to respond to alarms despatched by non-graded companies and insurers may also deny a claim where an insured customer's system was monitored by an ungraded provider.
[src:crash-bar/alarm-monitoring-center] The Australian Security Industry Association Limited (ASIAL) runs a grading scheme and publishes a list of graded monitoring centres.
[src:crash-bar/alarm-monitoring-center] In the UK a similar structure of auditing takes place, with the National Approval Council for Security Systems provision of inspection and certification.
[src:crash-bar/alarm-monitoring-center] Numerous standards such as BS5979 must be adhered to in order for a central station to be allowed to pass alerts to the police force.
[src:crash-bar/alarm-monitoring-center] Emerging European standards are superseding these at this time.
[src:crash-bar/area-of-refuge] An **area of refuge** or **safe room** is a place in a building designed to hold occupants during a fire or other emergency when evacuation may not be safe or possible.
[src:crash-bar/area-of-refuge] Occupants can wait there until rescued or relieved by firefighters.
[src:crash-bar/area-of-refuge] In some instances, an area of refuge or refuge area may refer to a designated space in a multi-unit residential building that can provide relief from unsafe or uncomfortable conditions in individual units.
[src:crash-bar/area-of-refuge] An area of refuge is typically supplied with a steady supply of fresh or filtered outside air.
[src:crash-bar/area-of-refuge] A two way communication system is provided on each floor above or below the main floor.
[src:crash-bar/area-of-refuge] A call box is required in each area of refuge, which can call into a central location called a base station.
[src:crash-bar/area-of-refuge] If the station is not attended 24 hours a day, the call must automatically call to an outside location and have two-way voice person to person communication capabilities.
[src:crash-bar/area-of-refuge] Such locations are usually required to be bounded by fire-resistant walls and floors.
[src:crash-bar/area-of-refuge] In the context of climate change, where older buildings may not be designed for changing climate conditions, refuge spaces are sometimes discussed in terms of providing communal areas in multi-unit buildings for when temperature and air quality is not safe or comfortable in individual units.
[src:crash-bar/arrow-lock] An **arrow lock** is a lock with standard dimensions used by the United States Postal Service for mail carriers to access collection boxes, outdoor parcel lockers, cluster box units, and apartment mailbox panels.
[src:crash-bar/arrow-lock] Arrow locks are unlocked through the use of a corresponding *arrow key*.
[src:crash-bar/arrow-lock] Arrow locks are also referred to as **Master Access Locks**.
[src:crash-bar/arrow-lock] An arrow lock is metal and rectangular, measuring 2.005 in × 3.566 in × 0.620 in (50.9 mm × 90.6 mm × 15.7 mm) with a keyhole in the center.
[src:crash-bar/arrow-lock] When the user turns the key, a metal bar that normally protrudes from one side is moved through the lock to the other side.
[src:crash-bar/arrow-lock] This action may be used to release a door (as in the case of a collection or parcel box) or to press/release a switch (as in the case of an electronic door release).
[src:crash-bar/arrow-lock] Arrow locks have four mounting holes, which are evenly spaced at the corners, providing for secure attachment to four 10-32 threaded studs with metal nuts.
[src:crash-bar/arrow-lock] A 7⁄8 in (22 mm) hole in the mounting surface is necessary to accommodate the keyhole, which protrudes above the surface of the lock.
[src:crash-bar/arrow-lock] USPS approved parcel lockers, cluster box units, and apartment mailbox panels will be manufactured with the hole and studs to accommodate an arrow lock.
[src:crash-bar/arrow-lock] In addition to actual mail delivery receptacles, arrow locks can also be found in key keepers, which are small lock boxes containing another key to a secured area where the mail receptacles are located.
[src:crash-bar/arrow-lock] Similar to knox boxes, key keepers secured with an arrow lock allow postal carriers to access the lobby of unstaffed multifamily buildings to deliver mail.
[src:crash-bar/arrow-lock] Conversion locks are available that match the mechanism and dimensions of USPS arrow locks, but are keyed for private use.
[src:crash-bar/arrow-lock] To obtain a new or replacement arrow lock, a property owner or manager must contact their local post office branch.
[src:crash-bar/arrow-lock] The arrow lock will be installed by USPS personnel.
[src:crash-bar/arrow-lock] Arrow keys are meticulously accounted for, and postal workers must check them out and return them daily.
[src:crash-bar/arrow-lock] When checked out, the arrow key is connected to the postal worker's uniform with a chain to make it harder to misplace.
[src:crash-bar/arrow-lock] A United States Postal Service Office of Inspector General audit in 2020 found the controls to be ineffective.
[src:crash-bar/arrow-lock] It stated that the number of arrow keys in circulation is unknown and keys are not adequately reported lost or stolen.
[src:crash-bar/arrow-lock] Lost or stolen arrow keys have been used by criminals to gain entry to apartment buildings and steal mail, often to commit identity theft.
[src:crash-bar/arrow-lock] Some criminals may also create counterfeit arrow keys to gain access.
[src:crash-bar/arrow-lock] Arrow keys have been the subject of increasing security concern in the United States due to rising theft and misuse.
[src:crash-bar/arrow-lock] Arrow keys operate within a master-key system that allows a single key to open multiple collection boxes and centralized mail receptacles.
[src:crash-bar/arrow-lock] The underlying master-key locking architecture dates to the early 20th century, with systems of this type in use by the U.S.
[src:crash-bar/arrow-lock] Post Office Department by the early 1920s.
[src:crash-bar/arrow-lock] Publicly reported data indicate a substantial increase in arrow-key thefts beginning in 2020.
[src:crash-bar/arrow-lock] Postal Service Office of Inspector General (OIG) audits and congressional testimony, reported incidents rose from approximately 1,374 in 2020 to 3,437 in 2024, representing an increase of roughly 150 percent over that period.
[src:crash-bar/arrow-lock] Recovery rates for stolen arrow keys remained low throughout this period, with fewer than 10 percent recovered in most reported years.
[src:crash-bar/arrow-lock] In addition to documented thefts, law-enforcement agencies and prosecutors have reported the circulation of counterfeit arrow keys within criminal markets.
[src:crash-bar/arrow-lock] Court filings and press statements indicate that counterfeit keys can be manufactured or acquired without the physical theft of an original key, potentially expanding unauthorized access beyond what is reflected in reported theft statistics.
[src:crash-bar/arrow-lock] Security analysts have noted that reliance on a master-key architecture creates systemic risk, as the compromise of a single key can provide access to numerous mail receptacles.
[src:crash-bar/arrow-lock] These vulnerabilities have been linked to broader concerns involving mail theft, check fraud, and identity theft, and have prompted calls from oversight bodies for modernization of mailbox locking systems and expanded preventive security measures.
[src:crash-bar/arrow-lock] The Post Office has announced "Project Safe Delivery" to combat postal theft and tampering.
[src:crash-bar/arrow-lock] In some areas of the US, the Post Office has started to use proprietary electronic locks ("eArrow") to allow their personnel to have secure access to buildings or mailboxes.
[src:crash-bar/arthur-b-guise-medal] Guise Medal** was established in 1983 and has been awarded annually starting in 1985 by the Society of Fire Protection Engineers.
[src:crash-bar/arthur-b-guise-medal] Named in memory of Arthur Guise, an engineer who developed dry chemicals as fire extinguishing agents, it recognizes eminent achievement in the advancement of the science and technology of fire protection engineering.
[src:crash-bar/crash-bar] A **crash bar** (also known as a **panic** **exit device, panic bar,** or **bump bar**) is a type of door opening mechanism which allows users to open a door by pushing a bar.
[src:crash-bar/crash-bar] While originally conceived as a way to prevent crowd crushing in an emergency, crash bars are now used as the primary door opening mechanism in many commercial buildings.
[src:crash-bar/crash-bar] The device consists of a spring-loaded metal bar which is fixed horizontally to a door that swings in the direction of an exit.
[src:crash-bar/crash-bar] Depressing the bar unlatches the door, allowing occupants to quickly leave the building.
[src:crash-bar/crash-bar] Modern fire standards often mandate that doors be fitted with crash bars in commercial and other occupancies where mass evacuation may be slowed by other types of door openers.
[src:crash-bar/crash-bar] They are sometimes intended solely for emergency use and may be fitted with alarms.
[src:crash-bar/crash-bar] However, in many buildings the crash bar is the primary mechanism for opening a door in normal circumstances as well.
[src:crash-bar/crash-bar] They may even be used when not required by code, because they are quicker and easier to use compared with a knob or lever handle.
[src:crash-bar/crash-bar] Following the events of the Victoria Hall disaster in Sunderland, England, in 1883 in which 183 children died because a door had been bolted at the bottom of a stairwell, the British government began legal moves to enforce minimum standards for building safety.
[src:crash-bar/crash-bar] This slowly led to the legal requirement that venues must have a minimum number of outward opening doors as well as locks which could be opened from the inside.
[src:crash-bar/crash-bar] Motivated by the Victoria Hall disaster, Robert Alexander Briggs (1868–1963) invented the panic bolt mechanism with horizontal bar which was granted a UK patent on 13 August 1892.
[src:crash-bar/crash-bar] However, these moves were not globally copied.
[src:crash-bar/crash-bar] For example, in the United States, at least 602 people died in the Iroquois Theatre fire in Chicago in December 1903 because of door latch designs that were difficult for fleeing patrons to open.
[src:crash-bar/crash-bar] A survivor of the Iroquois Theater fire, Carl Prinzler, along with architect Henry H.
[src:crash-bar/crash-bar] Dupont, independently developed and were awarded a series of nine patents relating to new and improved exit door hardware.
[src:crash-bar/crash-bar] All of the patent designs focused on a single lever bar (and related hardware) that would cause a locked door to pop open when simple interior pressure was exerted upon it.
[src:crash-bar/crash-bar] The bar would be mounted waist high from the ground.
[src:crash-bar/crash-bar] Five years later, 174 people in Ohio died in the Collinwood school fire, which led to a national outcry in the United States for greater fire safety in buildings.
[src:crash-bar/crash-bar] On 31 December 1929, some 37 years after the panic bolt was patented, 71 children died during the Glen Cinema disaster at a Hogmanay film screening in Paisley, Renfrewshire, Scotland, when a smoking cellulose nitrate film canister sparked panic.
[src:crash-bar/crash-bar] Children rushing to escape the cinema became crushed against the padlocked exit doors.
[src:crash-bar/crash-bar] Even after a police officer broke a padlock, the inward-opening doors were held shut by the mass of bodies behind them.
[src:crash-bar/crash-bar] By the end of the 20th century, most countries had building codes (or regulations) which require all public buildings have a minimum number of fire and emergency exits.
[src:crash-bar/crash-bar] Crash bars are fitted to these types of doors because they are proven to save lives in the event of human crushes.
[src:crash-bar/crash-bar] Panic can often occur during mass building evacuations caused by fires or explosions.
[src:crash-bar/crash-bar] In the event emergency exits are required, the crash bar works efficiently to allow people to pass through security doors without a reduction in speed.
[src:crash-bar/crash-bar] A crash bar's fast-acting mechanism reduces the risk that a rushing crowd might suddenly become a logjam at the exits.
[src:crash-bar/crash-bar] Such a human crush, which has many historical precedents, can cause falls, crushing, and other injury because the rear of a crowd has no idea that the people at the front of a crowd are impeded by a door.
[src:crash-bar/crash-bar] Crash bars are typically found on doors which are required emergency exits serving a particular type or quantity of occupants.
[src:crash-bar/crash-bar] Common locations include doors which provide egress from assembly areas, doors which serve many occupants, or doors serving hazardous areas.
[src:crash-bar/crash-bar] For buildings subject to the International Building Code or a locally adopted variation, they are required for certain healthcare, education, or assembly spaces, generally related to the number of occupants expected to exit quickly through a given door.
[src:crash-bar/crash-bar] Crash bars offer several configurations for latching to the door frame.
[src:crash-bar/crash-bar] Vertical rods can be affixed to crash bars allowing both doors to be opened with no center clearance obstruction.
[src:crash-bar/crash-bar] When the bar is depressed, a cord within the vertical rod gets pulled, which lowers a latch at the top and/or bottom and allows the door to open.
[src:crash-bar/crash-bar] The *Pullman latch*, which attaches to a Pullman keeper, is the locking mechanism usually used at the ends of the vertical rods.
[src:crash-bar/crash-bar] More expensive products may feature vertical rods and latches concealed within the door.
[src:crash-bar/crash-bar] Some jurisdictions permit doors to latch to each other.
[src:crash-bar/crash-bar] For security, additional latching points may be added.
[src:crash-bar/crash-bar] For example, upper and lower vertical rods added to one door and connected to the leaf with no rods via a mortice latch.
[src:crash-bar/crash-bar] A *double door coordinator* is used to ensure the active leaf does not close before the inactive leaf.
[src:crash-bar/crash-bar] This configuration is not recommended for high traffic locations.
[src:crash-bar/crash-bar] Center posts are an alternative to vertical rods at double door exits.
[src:crash-bar/crash-bar] This offers less clearance because the post remains in the middle when both doors are open.
[src:crash-bar/crash-bar] That said, the post can often be removed with a key for occasions when items larger than a single door need to pass through.
[src:crash-bar/crash-bar] Center posts may be preferred over vertical rods because they have fewer moving parts, thus they have fewer components that can wear out or break.
[src:crash-bar/crash-bar] Push bars themselves are some of the most reliable door opening mechanisms.
[src:crash-bar/crash-bar] To pass CE certification, bars must function between 100,000 and 500,000 opening cycles depending on the rating the manufacturer is seeking.
[src:crash-bar/crash-bar] In some applications, such as storefront entrances, panic bars may be "dogged" during business hours.
[src:crash-bar/crash-bar] Dogging is a common feature on panic bars in which the bar is retracted with a key, thus freeing the door to operate without latching.
[src:crash-bar/crash-bar] This allows customers to apply force to any portion of the door, not just the bar, in order to open it.
[src:crash-bar/crash-bar] Dogging is distinct from simple unlocking, which permits the user to open the door from both sides but still requires performing an action to release the latches.
[src:crash-bar/crash-bar] However, in applications where the exterior side contains an immovable *dummy handle*, as opposed to a knob or lever handle, it is usually impossible to unlock the crash bar without also dogging it.
[src:crash-bar/crash-bar] Dogging can extend the life of the panic bar mechanism.
[src:crash-bar/crash-bar] Some bars can be unlocked/dogged electronically, while others take a cylinder lock, hex key, or contain no key functionality at all.
[src:crash-bar/crash-bar] Dogging should be avoided in high wind areas where the door is susceptible to blowing open.
[src:crash-bar/crash-bar] Unlike a traditional crash bar, this type contains a horizontal touch sensor and no moving parts.
[src:crash-bar/crash-bar] When the sensor is pressed, it releases an electromagnetic lock.
[src:crash-bar/crash-bar] It may be used in tandem with a motion sensor which unlocks for anyone who stands in front of the door, or an emergency exit button.
[src:crash-bar/crash-bar] This type of release must still unlock in the event of a power failure, and in some jurisdictions, the door must automatically unlock for a fire alarm activation, must unlock for a duration of thirty (30) seconds upon each unlock duration, and must not have secondary power, such as a battery backup.
[src:crash-bar/crash-bar] Because these will not function in a long term power outage, they are most commonly used on secondary doors between a vestibule and the secure part of a building.
[src:crash-bar/crash-bar] In some jurisdictions, when automatic doors are used on the primary exit route, these doors are equipped with crash bars.
[src:crash-bar/crash-bar] In the event the automatic door does not function, it becomes an outward swinging rather than sliding door.
[src:crash-bar/crash-bar] Crash bars are one of many emergency release mechanisms that can be used with automatic doors.
[src:crash-bar/crash-bar] Depending on available space, a common alternative is to install an emergency exit door beside the automatic doors.
[src:crash-bar/crash-bar] Installation of a secondary crash bar equipped exit is often required in large buildings with revolving doors, since these are too slow for a crowd to move through.
[src:crash-bar/crash-bar] In the European Union, panic bars are governed by the standard *EN 1125*, *Panic exit devices operated by a horizontal bar*.
[src:crash-bar/crash-bar] As with other EN family standards, the English language version is produced by the British Standards Institution and utilises the call sign BS EN 1125.
[src:crash-bar/crash-bar] Panic bars are required to conform to this standard in order to carry CE marking and thus be sold in the European Economic Area.
[src:crash-bar/crash-bar] In 2008, the standard was updated to include an alpha-numeric labelling scheme.
[src:crash-bar/crash-bar] In this system, products are tested to various benchmarks and assigned a letter or number accordingly.
[src:crash-bar/crash-bar] Products must achieve minimum quality scores in order to receive general CE approval.
[src:crash-bar/crash-bar] EN 1125 is one of two standards which govern exit devices in the EU.
[src:crash-bar/crash-bar] The other standard, EN 179, governs door handles, push pads, and other exit devices with emergency release functionality.
[src:crash-bar/crash-bar] However, EN 179 devices shall only be used at locations where people "are familiar with the emergency exit and its hardware and therefore a panic situation is unlikely to appear".
[src:crash-bar/crash-bar] Examples of places where EN 179 hardware may be used in place of EN 1125 panic bars include small apartment buildings and offices.
[src:crash-bar/crash-bar] The first panic bar, made by Von Duprin, was available by 1908 in many models and configurations.
[src:crash-bar/crash-bar] In the US, building exit requirements are generally controlled by model codes such as the International Building Code and the NFPA Life Safety Code.
[src:crash-bar/crash-bar] Adoption of regulations varies by location and may occur at the city, county, or state level.
[src:crash-bar/crash-bar] Model codes are usually supplemented with amendments adopted locally.
[src:crash-bar/crash-bar] Additional requirements may be imposed on a site from an authority having jurisdiction such as a local fire marshal.
[src:crash-bar/crash-bar] Factors considered when mandating exit devices include the number of occupants who would need to leave in an emergency, the availability of other nearby exits, and proximity to any hazards equipment or chemicals.
[src:crash-bar/crash-bar] In Europe, most panic bars are of the cross bar type, which are called Type A in the EN 1125 standard.
[src:crash-bar/crash-bar] This contrasts strongly with North American architectural design, which years ago switched to using predominantly touch bars (EN 1125 Type B) in new construction.
[src:crash-bar/crash-bar] In Europe, the use of panic bars is generally confined to code required applications.
[src:crash-bar/crash-bar] In US and Canadian commercial buildings, they are frequently used even where not required by code, because bars are seen as being easier to use than knobs or lever handles.
[src:crash-bar/crash-bar] For example, when used on the rear service door of a business, a worker whose hands are being used to carry bulky items can lean against a bar to release the lock.
[src:crash-bar/crash-bar] While the public generally prefers automatic doors, they can be costly to install and maintain.
[src:crash-bar/crash-bar] Some manufacturers offer crash bars designed to resist microbial growth.
[src:crash-bar/crash-bar] This can include coating the bar with silver ions in order to create a chemical environment hostile to unwanted microbes.
[src:crash-bar/crash-bar] Antimicrobial surfaces have shown to be effective at inhibiting bacterial, mold, and mildew growth; but may not be effective at stopping viruses such as SARS-CoV-2.
